draw((0,10)..(3,19)..(6,22)..(24,22)..(27,19)..(30,10)..(27,1)..(24,-2)..(15,-5),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((15,0)--(15,-5),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((15,-5)..(11.4645,-3.5355)..(10,0),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
label("1",(15,0)--(15,-5),W);
label("2",(15,0)--(15,10),E);
label("3",(0,10)--(15,10),N);
[/asy]

This area is a $90^\circ$ sector of a circle of radius $1,$ or $\frac{1}{4}$ of this circle.  So this additional area is $$\frac{1}{4} \times \pi (1^2)=\frac{1}{4}\pi.$$ So the total area that Chuck has in which to play is $$\frac{27}{4}\pi + \frac{1}{4}\pi = \frac{28}{4}\pi = \boxed{7\pi}\text{ m}^2.$$. The answer is 7\pi

